{"title_page": "East Cobb, Georgia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = East Cobb, Georgia\n|official_name            = \n|settlement_type          = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated community]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Chadds Lake Drive, East Cobb, Georgia April 2017.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = A subdivision in East Cobb\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = Metro Atlanta\n|pushpin_label = East Cobb\n|pushpin_label_position   = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location within [[Metro Atlanta]]\n|pushpin_mapsize          =\n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              = Location within Cobb County\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Georgia|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Cobb County, Georgia|Cobb]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = <!-- Mayor -->\n|leader_name              =\n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = 2007 \n|population_footnotes     = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/city/Northeast-Cobb-Georgia.html|title=Northeast Cobb, Georgia (GA 30062) profile: population, maps, real estate, averages, homes, statistics, relocation, travel, jobs, hospitals, schools, crime, moving, houses, news, sex offenders|website=City-data.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n|population_total         = 169,756 (Northeast Cobb CCD)\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_ft             = \n|coordinates              = {{coord|33|57|58|N|84|24|41|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s \n|postal_code              = 30062, 30066, 30068, 30067, 30075\n|area_code                = [[Area code 770|770]]/[[Area codes 678 and 470|678/470/404]]\n|blank_name               = \n|blank_info               = \n|blank1_name              = \n|blank1_info              = \n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''East Cobb''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Cobb County, Georgia]], United States, with a population of about 175,890 people. It is an affluent northern suburb of [[Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://realtytimes.com/rtpages/20050729_atlantasuburb.htm|title=Home|website=realtytimes.com|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311084143/http://realtytimes.com/rtpages/20050729_atlantasuburb.htm|archive-date=11 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nEast Cobb is roughly bounded by:\n* [[Cherokee County, Georgia|Cherokee County]] to the north\n* Willeo Creek and [[Roswell, Georgia|Roswell]] in [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]] to the northeast\n* the [[Chattahoochee River]] and [[Sandy Springs, Georgia|Sandy Springs]] in Fulton County to the southeast\n* [[historic ferries of the Atlanta area#Bell's Ferry|Bell's Ferry]] Road, [[Interstate 575|I-575]], and the [[Marietta, Georgia|Marietta]] [[city limit]]s to the west, and\n* [[Interstate 285 (Georgia)|Interstate 285]] and the [[Cumberland/Galleria]] [[edge city]] at the southern tip.\n\nNo part of East Cobb technically falls within incorporated city limits. East Cobb consists primarily of unincorporated areas near Marietta, and a significant portion of unincorporated area near [[Roswell, Georgia|Roswell]], as defined by [[United States Postal Service]] [[ZIP code]]s (though Roswell itself was in Cobb until 1932).  A small sliver of an unincorporated area near Atlanta is in the extreme southern tip near [[Vinings, Georgia|Vinings]], and a portion of the northwest is in  an unincorporated area near [[Kennesaw, Georgia|Kennesaw]] (30144). ZIP codes that are associated with this area are (30144), (30188), (30062), (30066), (30067), (30068), and some of (30075).  Creekway Drive in unincorporated Cobb County is not considered to be within East Cobb by any recognized authority.\n\nEast Cobb does not fall within any [[census-designated place]], but within the Northeast Cobb [[census county division]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/blk2000/st13_Georgia/County/13067_Cobb/CBC13067_000.pdf|title=\"Census 2000 Block Map, Cobb County\", US Census Bureau|website=2.census.gov|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSmall communities, many established early in the area's post-[[Cherokee]] history, include Mount Bethel (located in present day central East Cobb), Shallowford Falls, Sandy Plains, [[Noonday, Georgia|Noonday]], Blackwells, and Westoak.  The area was developed as a suburb of Atlanta beginning in the 1960s. The \"city\" of [[Chattahoochee Plantation]], which never had a [[city government]], was established along the river by the [[Georgia General Assembly]] entirely to prevent Atlanta from [[annexation]] in 1961, and was officially abolished in 1995 along with dozens of other Georgia towns with defunct governments.\n\n===Incorporation as a city===\nIn contrast to other northern suburbs of Atlanta, East Cobb has remained [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated]]. The idea of incorporating East Cobb as a city was suggested in 2009 by the organization \"Citizens for the City of East Cobb\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cityofeastcobb.org/about/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725173058/http://www.cityofeastcobb.org/about/ |archive-date=25 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Yet the first serious discussion of incorporating East Cobb was initiated in 1998 by then Cobb County chairman  Bill Byrne.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/19755515/article-East-Cobbers-voice-mixed-reactions-to-idea-about-forming-city |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813195023/http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/19755515/article-East-Cobbers-voice-mixed-reactions-to-idea-about-forming-city |archive-date=13 August 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Under Byrne's proposal, the city's boundary lines would be drawn by the Cobb Legislative Delegation, the county government would continue to provide water, sewer, police and fire services to the city for a nominal fee of one dollar per year, and the city would be governed by an elected mayor and five City Council members, with wards drawn by the Cobb Delegation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/19737517/article-Byrne-floats-idea-for-an-East-Cobb-city |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813044330/http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/19737517/article-Byrne-floats-idea-for-an-East-Cobb-city |archive-date=13 August 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, Byrne was defeated by Cobb County Chairman Incumbent Tim Lee, who dismissed the idea of incorporating East Cobb as \"solution looking for a problem.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.11alive.com/news/article/252130/3/Could-East-Cobb-be-Georgias-newest-city- |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 December 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116010251/http://www.11alive.com/news/article/252130/3/Could-East-Cobb-be-Georgias-newest-city- |archive-date=16 January 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In March 2019, Matt Dollar, a local representative in the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] announced that he would be submitting a bill to create the legislation necessary for East Cobb cityhood. The bill could not be approved by the legislature or by referendum until 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lutz |first1=Meris |title=Marietta lawmaker to file bill for city of East Cobb |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/marietta-lawmaker-file-bill-for-city-east-cobb/c45kh6qhbquu45SMy42UuM/ |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=20 March 2019}}</ref> If East Cobb were to incorporate as a city, it would be the largest in the county and the second largest in [[Atlanta metropolitan area|metro Atlanta]] (behind [[Atlanta]]), with around 150,000 residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yLN0dsWN57EC&pg=PA110&dq=east+cobb+georgia&hl=en&ei=_I-lTPufK4nCsAPz5fj9Dg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=east+cobb+georgia&f=false|title=Cobb County|first1=Rebecca Nash|last1=Paden|first2=Joe|last2=McTyre|date=11 July 2018|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|accessdate=11 July 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n===Shopping===\n'''Merchant's Walk''' is a {{convert|367600|sqft|m2|adj=on}} open-air shopping center with retailers, restaurants, and a movie theater originally built in 1976 and since expanded and twice renovated, once in the early 1990s and again in 2008\u20132011. The ''East Cobber'' newspaper called the center the \"heart\" of the East Cobb community.<ref>[http://www.eastcobber.com/merchants-walk-makes-changes \"Merchant's Walk makes changes\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826114736/http://www.eastcobber.com/merchants-walk-makes-changes |date=26 August 2014 }}, ''East Cobber'', 2012-01-19</ref> Tenants include Cook's Warehouse, [[Kohl's]], [[Stein Mart]], [[PetsMart]], [[ULTA Beauty]], [[Old Navy]], [[Whole Foods Market]], Marlow's Tavern, and SEED Kitchen & Bar, as well as a movie theater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edens.com/centers/GA/Marietta/Merchant's-Walk|title=Our Places - EDENS|website=EDENS|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref> The center is located at the intersection of [[Johnson Ferry]] and Roswell Roads.\n\nEast Cobb Library was once located in Merchant's Walk; it has since relocated to Parkaire, a nearby strip of stores on Johnson Ferry Road.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eastcobb.patch.com/listings/merchants-walk |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222010/http://eastcobb.patch.com/listings/merchants-walk |archive-date=2 December 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n'''The Avenue East Cobb''' is a {{convert|236189|sqft|m2|adj=on|0}} open-air shopping center at 4475 [[Roswell Road]] anchored by a [[Bed Bath & Beyond]] and [[Michaels]] arts and crafts store. It has a horseshoe-shaped form and a \"period-style Main Street design\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmharch.com/projects/retail_entertainment/lifestyle_centers/the_avenue_east_cobb.html|title=Page at CMH Architects|website=Cmharch.com|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224005654/http://www.cmharch.com/projects/retail_entertainment/lifestyle_centers/the_avenue_east_cobb.html|archive-date=24 February 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and \"town square\" concepts,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dougharch.com/Portfolio/CompletedPortfolio/LifestyleCenters/TheAvenueEastCobb/tabid/588/Default.aspx|title=Dougherty Architectural Consulting > Portfolio > Completed Portfolio > Lifestyle Centers > The Avenue East Cobb|first=Dougherty Architectural|last=Consulting|website=Dougharch.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref> according to its designers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/articles/Avenue-East-Cobb-Marietta-Atlanta.html|title=Avenue East Cobb - Marietta (Atlanta), Georgia - Open-Air Retail Shopping Center with Dining and Entertainment|website=City-data.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eastcobb.shoptheavenue.com/stores|title=\"Stores\", The Avenue East Cobb website|website=Eastcobb.shoptheavenue.com|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826115234/http://eastcobb.shoptheavenue.com/stores|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Paper Mill Village''' is a collection of 33 buildings linked by over a mile of pedestrian walkways. The Village includes retail tenants, restaurant tenants, and service provider tenants. The village also hosts a monthly food truck night from April\u2013October each year on the last Monday of each month.\n\n== Culture ==\nA popular community event is the Taste of East Cobb, held annually. The YMCA operates the McKlesky Family-East Cobb YMCA at 1055 East Piedmont Road. East Cobb park is a popular recreational area for the community. The community is also home to a civic association, a Kiwanis Club, and a Rotary Club.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://prca.cobbcountyga.gov/EastCobbPark.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614033928/http://prca.cobbcountyga.gov/EastCobbPark.htm |archive-date=14 June 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubrunner.ca/CPrg/home/homeS.asp?cid=5411|title=Home Page - Rotary Club of East Cobb|website=Clubrunner.ca|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.eastcobbkiwanis.org/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105025804/http://www.eastcobbkiwanis.org/ |archive-date=5 November 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tasteofeastcobb.com|title=Taste of East Cobb|website=Tasteofeastcobb.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ymcaatlanta.org/Branches/MCY-McCleskey_Cobb_YMCA/default.asp] {{dead link|date=July 2018}}</ref> The paper-only weekly ''East Cobb Neighbor'' has a circulation of around 44,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-media.com/mediaDetail.php?ID=4305|title=Echo Media V3 Print Media Experts|website=Echo Media V3|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mondotimes.com/1/world/us/10/606/21364|title=East Cobb Neighbor newspaper - MondoTimes.com|website=Mondotimes.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nEast Cobb is home to some of metro Atlanta's largest churches. Johnson Ferry Baptist Church, located between Johnson Ferry Road and Woodlawn Drive, has roughly 7,500 members. Mt. Bethel United Methodist Church, located off of Lower Roswell Road by the Cobb County Government Center, has over 9,000 members. The Catholic Church of St. Ann is located at the corner of Bishop Lake Road and Roswell Road as well. East Cobb is also home to three centers of Jewish life: [[Chabad]] of Cobb, Temple Kol Emeth ([[Reform Judaism]]), and Congregation Etz Chaim ([[Conservative Judaism]]).\n\n==Government==\nVarious neighborhood and subdivision community associations are represented within the overall East Cobb Civic Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastcobb.net/index.cfm/category/5/about-ecca.cfm|title=About - East Cobb, Georgia Home Owners Association, Civic Government - ECCA|website=Eastcobb.net|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref> which promotes dialog between government and community organizations and seeks to shape county government policy and improve the community's quality of life. \nThe [[United States Postal Service]] operates the '''East Cobb Post Office''' branch.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usps.whitepages.com/service/post_office/east-cobb-station-1395-e-cobb-dr-marietta-ga-1361686 |title=Archived copy |access-date=30 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915104317/http://usps.whitepages.com/service/post_office/east-cobb-station-1395-e-cobb-dr-marietta-ga-1361686 |archive-date=15 September 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nCobb County operates the '''East Cobb Government Service Center'''. The center contains a county Police precinct, a Cobb Fire and Emergency Services station, and a Tag (license plate) Office. East Cobb comprises districts 2 and 3 of the [[Cobb County, Georgia#Government and elections|Cobb County Commission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastcobb.net/index.cfm/category/32/your-county-commissioners.cfm|title=East Cobb Civic Association|website=Eastcobb.net|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723105301/http://www.eastcobb.net/index.cfm/category/32/your-county-commissioners.cfm|archive-date=23 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCobb County Public Library operates the '''East Cobb Library''' (formerly the Merchant's Walk Library).\n\n== Education ==\nPublic schools in East Cobb are part of the [[Cobb County School District]]. The area comprises several [[high school]] attendance districts: [[Pope High School|Pope]], [[Sprayberry High School|Sprayberry]], [[Joseph Wheeler High School|Wheeler]], [[Kell High School|Kell]], [[George Walton Comprehensive High School|Walton]], and [[Lassiter High School|Lassiter]]. The western half of the Kell district lies outside of East Cobb. The extreme western portion of the Sprayberry district (the [[Town Center at Cobb|Town Center Mall]] area) also lies outside of East Cobb. The extreme southwestern and southern portions of the Wheeler district lie west of I-75 and south of I-285 respectively, thus excluding these small areas from being considered a part of East Cobb.\n\nThe area known as East Cobb comprises the following [[middle school]] districts: Daniell, McCleskey, Simpson, Hightower Trail, Mabry, [[East Cobb Middle School|East Cobb]], Dodgen, and [[Dickerson Middle School|Dickerson]] (small portions of the Daniell and East Cobb Middle School districts lie outside of East Cobb; a sliver of the eastern portion of the Palmer Middle School district can be considered a part of East Cobb).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cobbk12.org/centraloffice/planning/zonemaps.aspx|title=Planning|website=Cobbk12.org|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people==\n<!---needs to have footnote with \"East Cobb\" claimed by notable--->\n*[[Alton Brown]], food and media personality\n*[[Blaine Boyer]], professional baseball player\n*[[Brett Butler (actress)|Brett Butler]], comedian\n*[[Bobby Cox]], former manager of the [[Atlanta Braves]]\n*[[Jimmy De Martini]], musician; member of the [[Zac Brown Band]]\n*[[Missy Elliott]], musician\n*[[Newt Gingrich]], Former [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]], 2012 Republican Presidential candidate\n*[[Johnny Isakson]], United States Senator\n*[[Lester Maddox]], former restaurant owner and governor of Georgia; resided in East Cobb before his death\n*[[Ty Pennington]], Sprayberry High graduate, ''[[Extreme Home Makeover]]'' and ''[[Trading Spaces]]''\n*[[Cody Rhodes]], professional wrestler\n*[[Chris Robinson (singer)|Chris Robinson]] and [[Rich Robinson]] of [[The Black Crowes]]\n*[[Tony Schiavone]], former announcer for WCW, currently radio sports announcer, producer, engineer\n*[[Travis Tritt]], country music star\n*[[Lawson Vaughn]], professional soccer player\n*[[T. J. Yates]], NFL quarterback\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=yLN0dsWN57EC&pg=PA110&dq=east+cobb+georgia&hl=en&ei=_I-lTPufK4nCsAPz5fj9Dg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=east%20cobb%20georgia&f=false Rebecca Nash Paden, Joe McTyre, ''Cobb County'']\n\n{{Cobb County, Georgia}}\n{{Atlanta Metro}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Cobb County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Chattahoochee River]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = East Cobb, Georgia\n|official_name            = \n|settlement_type          = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated community]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Chadds Lake Drive, East Cobb, Georgia April 2017.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = A subdivision in East Cobb\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = Metro Atlanta\n|pushpin_label = East Cobb\n|pushpin_label_position   = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location within [[Metro Atlanta]]\n|pushpin_mapsize          =\n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              = Location within Cobb County\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Georgia|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Cobb County, Georgia|Cobb]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = <!-- Mayor -->\n|leader_name              =\n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = 2007 \n|population_footnotes     = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/city/Northeast-Cobb-Georgia.html|title=Northeast Cobb, Georgia (GA 30062) profile: population, maps, real estate, averages, homes, statistics, relocation, travel, jobs, hospitals, schools, crime, moving, houses, news, sex offenders|website=City-data.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n|population_total         = 169,756 (Northeast Cobb CCD)\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_ft             = \n|coordinates              = {{coord|33|57|58|N|84|24|41|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s \n|postal_code              = 30062, 30066, 30068, 30067, 30075\n|area_code                = [[Area code 770|770]]/[[Area codes 678 and 470|678/470/404]]\n|blank_name               = \n|blank_info               = \n|blank1_name              = \n|blank1_info              = \n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''East Cobb''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Cobb County, Georgia]], United States, with a population of about 175,890 people. It is an affluent northern suburb of [[Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://realtytimes.com/rtpages/20050729_atlantasuburb.htm|title=Home|website=realtytimes.com|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311084143/http://realtytimes.com/rtpages/20050729_atlantasuburb.htm|archive-date=11 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nEast Cobb is roughly bounded by:\n* [[Cherokee County, Georgia|Cherokee County]] to the north\n* Willeo Creek and [[Roswell, Georgia|Roswell]] in [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]] to the northeast\n* the [[Chattahoochee River]] and [[Sandy Springs, Georgia|Sandy Springs]] in Fulton County to the southeast\n* [[historic ferries of the Atlanta area#Bell's Ferry|Bell's Ferry]] Road, [[Interstate 575|I-575]], and the [[Marietta, Georgia|Marietta]] [[city limit]]s to the west, and\n* [[Interstate 285 (Georgia)|Interstate 285]] and the [[Cumberland/Galleria]] [[edge city]] at the southern tip.\n\nNo part of East Cobb technically falls within incorporated city limits. East Cobb consists primarily of unincorporated areas near Marietta, and a significant portion of unincorporated area near [[Roswell, Georgia|Roswell]], as defined by [[United States Postal Service]] [[ZIP code]]s (though Roswell itself was in Cobb until 1932).  A small sliver of an unincorporated area near Atlanta is in the extreme southern tip near [[Vinings, Georgia|Vinings]], and a portion of the northwest is in  an unincorporated area near [[Kennesaw, Georgia|Kennesaw]] (30144). ZIP codes that are associated with this area are (30144), (30188), (30062), (30066), (30067), (30068), and some of (30075).\n\nEast Cobb does not fall within any [[census-designated place]], but within the Northeast Cobb [[census county division]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/blk2000/st13_Georgia/County/13067_Cobb/CBC13067_000.pdf|title=\"Census 2000 Block Map, Cobb County\", US Census Bureau|website=2.census.gov|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSmall communities, many established early in the area's post-[[Cherokee]] history, include Mount Bethel (located in present day central East Cobb), Shallowford Falls, Sandy Plains, [[Noonday, Georgia|Noonday]], Blackwells, and Westoak.  The area was developed as a suburb of Atlanta beginning in the 1960s. The \"city\" of [[Chattahoochee Plantation]], which never had a [[city government]], was established along the river by the [[Georgia General Assembly]] entirely to prevent Atlanta from [[annexation]] in 1961, and was officially abolished in 1995 along with dozens of other Georgia towns with defunct governments.\n\n===Incorporation as a city===\nIn contrast to other northern suburbs of Atlanta, East Cobb has remained [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated]]. The idea of incorporating East Cobb as a city was suggested in 2009 by the organization \"Citizens for the City of East Cobb\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cityofeastcobb.org/about/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725173058/http://www.cityofeastcobb.org/about/ |archive-date=25 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Yet the first serious discussion of incorporating East Cobb was initiated in 1998 by then Cobb County chairman  Bill Byrne.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/19755515/article-East-Cobbers-voice-mixed-reactions-to-idea-about-forming-city |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813195023/http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/19755515/article-East-Cobbers-voice-mixed-reactions-to-idea-about-forming-city |archive-date=13 August 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Under Byrne's proposal, the city's boundary lines would be drawn by the Cobb Legislative Delegation, the county government would continue to provide water, sewer, police and fire services to the city for a nominal fee of one dollar per year, and the city would be governed by an elected mayor and five City Council members, with wards drawn by the Cobb Delegation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/19737517/article-Byrne-floats-idea-for-an-East-Cobb-city |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813044330/http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/19737517/article-Byrne-floats-idea-for-an-East-Cobb-city |archive-date=13 August 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, Byrne was defeated by Cobb County Chairman Incumbent Tim Lee, who dismissed the idea of incorporating East Cobb as \"solution looking for a problem.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.11alive.com/news/article/252130/3/Could-East-Cobb-be-Georgias-newest-city- |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 December 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116010251/http://www.11alive.com/news/article/252130/3/Could-East-Cobb-be-Georgias-newest-city- |archive-date=16 January 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In March 2019, Matt Dollar, a local representative in the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] announced that he would be submitting a bill to create the legislation necessary for East Cobb cityhood. The bill could not be approved by the legislature or by referendum until 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lutz |first1=Meris |title=Marietta lawmaker to file bill for city of East Cobb |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/marietta-lawmaker-file-bill-for-city-east-cobb/c45kh6qhbquu45SMy42UuM/ |accessdate=21 March 2019 |work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=20 March 2019}}</ref> If East Cobb were to incorporate as a city, it would be the largest in the county and the second largest in [[Atlanta metropolitan area|metro Atlanta]] (behind [[Atlanta]]), with around 150,000 residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yLN0dsWN57EC&pg=PA110&dq=east+cobb+georgia&hl=en&ei=_I-lTPufK4nCsAPz5fj9Dg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=east+cobb+georgia&f=false|title=Cobb County|first1=Rebecca Nash|last1=Paden|first2=Joe|last2=McTyre|date=11 July 2018|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|accessdate=11 July 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n===Shopping===\n'''Merchant's Walk''' is a {{convert|367600|sqft|m2|adj=on}} open-air shopping center with retailers, restaurants, and a movie theater originally built in 1976 and since expanded and twice renovated, once in the early 1990s and again in 2008\u20132011. The ''East Cobber'' newspaper called the center the \"heart\" of the East Cobb community.<ref>[http://www.eastcobber.com/merchants-walk-makes-changes \"Merchant's Walk makes changes\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826114736/http://www.eastcobber.com/merchants-walk-makes-changes |date=26 August 2014 }}, ''East Cobber'', 2012-01-19</ref> Tenants include Cook's Warehouse, [[Kohl's]], [[Stein Mart]], [[PetsMart]], [[ULTA Beauty]], [[Old Navy]], [[Whole Foods Market]], Marlow's Tavern, and SEED Kitchen & Bar, as well as a movie theater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edens.com/centers/GA/Marietta/Merchant's-Walk|title=Our Places - EDENS|website=EDENS|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref> The center is located at the intersection of [[Johnson Ferry]] and Roswell Roads.\n\nEast Cobb Library was once located in Merchant's Walk; it has since relocated to Parkaire, a nearby strip of stores on Johnson Ferry Road.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eastcobb.patch.com/listings/merchants-walk |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222010/http://eastcobb.patch.com/listings/merchants-walk |archive-date=2 December 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n'''The Avenue East Cobb''' is a {{convert|236189|sqft|m2|adj=on|0}} open-air shopping center at 4475 [[Roswell Road]] anchored by a [[Bed Bath & Beyond]] and [[Michaels]] arts and crafts store. It has a horseshoe-shaped form and a \"period-style Main Street design\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmharch.com/projects/retail_entertainment/lifestyle_centers/the_avenue_east_cobb.html|title=Page at CMH Architects|website=Cmharch.com|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224005654/http://www.cmharch.com/projects/retail_entertainment/lifestyle_centers/the_avenue_east_cobb.html|archive-date=24 February 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and \"town square\" concepts,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dougharch.com/Portfolio/CompletedPortfolio/LifestyleCenters/TheAvenueEastCobb/tabid/588/Default.aspx|title=Dougherty Architectural Consulting > Portfolio > Completed Portfolio > Lifestyle Centers > The Avenue East Cobb|first=Dougherty Architectural|last=Consulting|website=Dougharch.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref> according to its designers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/articles/Avenue-East-Cobb-Marietta-Atlanta.html|title=Avenue East Cobb - Marietta (Atlanta), Georgia - Open-Air Retail Shopping Center with Dining and Entertainment|website=City-data.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eastcobb.shoptheavenue.com/stores|title=\"Stores\", The Avenue East Cobb website|website=Eastcobb.shoptheavenue.com|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826115234/http://eastcobb.shoptheavenue.com/stores|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n'''Paper Mill Village''' is a collection of 33 buildings linked by over a mile of pedestrian walkways. The Village includes retail tenants, restaurant tenants, and service provider tenants. The village also hosts a monthly food truck night from April\u2013October each year on the last Monday of each month.\n\n== Culture ==\nA popular community event is the Taste of East Cobb, held annually. The YMCA operates the McKlesky Family-East Cobb YMCA at 1055 East Piedmont Road. East Cobb park is a popular recreational area for the community. The community is also home to a civic association, a Kiwanis Club, and a Rotary Club.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://prca.cobbcountyga.gov/EastCobbPark.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614033928/http://prca.cobbcountyga.gov/EastCobbPark.htm |archive-date=14 June 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubrunner.ca/CPrg/home/homeS.asp?cid=5411|title=Home Page - Rotary Club of East Cobb|website=Clubrunner.ca|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.eastcobbkiwanis.org/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105025804/http://www.eastcobbkiwanis.org/ |archive-date=5 November 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tasteofeastcobb.com|title=Taste of East Cobb|website=Tasteofeastcobb.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ymcaatlanta.org/Branches/MCY-McCleskey_Cobb_YMCA/default.asp] {{dead link|date=July 2018}}</ref> The paper-only weekly ''East Cobb Neighbor'' has a circulation of around 44,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-media.com/mediaDetail.php?ID=4305|title=Echo Media V3 Print Media Experts|website=Echo Media V3|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mondotimes.com/1/world/us/10/606/21364|title=East Cobb Neighbor newspaper - MondoTimes.com|website=Mondotimes.com|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nEast Cobb is home to some of metro Atlanta's largest churches. Johnson Ferry Baptist Church, located between Johnson Ferry Road and Woodlawn Drive, has roughly 7,500 members. Mt. Bethel United Methodist Church, located off of Lower Roswell Road by the Cobb County Government Center, has over 9,000 members. The Catholic Church of St. Ann is located at the corner of Bishop Lake Road and Roswell Road as well. East Cobb is also home to three centers of Jewish life: [[Chabad]] of Cobb, Temple Kol Emeth ([[Reform Judaism]]), and Congregation Etz Chaim ([[Conservative Judaism]]).\n\n==Government==\nVarious neighborhood and subdivision community associations are represented within the overall East Cobb Civic Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastcobb.net/index.cfm/category/5/about-ecca.cfm|title=About - East Cobb, Georgia Home Owners Association, Civic Government - ECCA|website=Eastcobb.net|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref> which promotes dialog between government and community organizations and seeks to shape county government policy and improve the community's quality of life. \nThe [[United States Postal Service]] operates the '''East Cobb Post Office''' branch.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usps.whitepages.com/service/post_office/east-cobb-station-1395-e-cobb-dr-marietta-ga-1361686 |title=Archived copy |access-date=30 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915104317/http://usps.whitepages.com/service/post_office/east-cobb-station-1395-e-cobb-dr-marietta-ga-1361686 |archive-date=15 September 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nCobb County operates the '''East Cobb Government Service Center'''. The center contains a county Police precinct, a Cobb Fire and Emergency Services station, and a Tag (license plate) Office. East Cobb comprises districts 2 and 3 of the [[Cobb County, Georgia#Government and elections|Cobb County Commission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastcobb.net/index.cfm/category/32/your-county-commissioners.cfm|title=East Cobb Civic Association|website=Eastcobb.net|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723105301/http://www.eastcobb.net/index.cfm/category/32/your-county-commissioners.cfm|archive-date=23 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCobb County Public Library operates the '''East Cobb Library''' (formerly the Merchant's Walk Library).\n\n== Education ==\nPublic schools in East Cobb are part of the [[Cobb County School District]]. The area comprises several [[high school]] attendance districts: [[Pope High School|Pope]], [[Sprayberry High School|Sprayberry]], [[Joseph Wheeler High School|Wheeler]], [[Kell High School|Kell]], [[George Walton Comprehensive High School|Walton]], and [[Lassiter High School|Lassiter]]. The western half of the Kell district lies outside of East Cobb. The extreme western portion of the Sprayberry district (the [[Town Center at Cobb|Town Center Mall]] area) also lies outside of East Cobb. The extreme southwestern and southern portions of the Wheeler district lie west of I-75 and south of I-285 respectively, thus excluding these small areas from being considered a part of East Cobb.\n\nThe area known as East Cobb comprises the following [[middle school]] districts: Daniell, McCleskey, Simpson, Hightower Trail, Mabry, [[East Cobb Middle School|East Cobb]], Dodgen, and [[Dickerson Middle School|Dickerson]] (small portions of the Daniell and East Cobb Middle School districts lie outside of East Cobb; a sliver of the eastern portion of the Palmer Middle School district can be considered a part of East Cobb).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cobbk12.org/centraloffice/planning/zonemaps.aspx|title=Planning|website=Cobbk12.org|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people==\n<!---needs to have footnote with \"East Cobb\" claimed by notable--->\n*[[Alton Brown]], food and media personality\n*[[Blaine Boyer]], professional baseball player\n*[[Brett Butler (actress)|Brett Butler]], comedian\n*[[Bobby Cox]], former manager of the [[Atlanta Braves]]\n*[[Jimmy De Martini]], musician; member of the [[Zac Brown Band]]\n*[[Missy Elliott]], musician\n*[[Newt Gingrich]], Former [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]], 2012 Republican Presidential candidate\n*[[Johnny Isakson]], United States Senator\n*[[Lester Maddox]], former restaurant owner and governor of Georgia; resided in East Cobb before his death\n*[[Ty Pennington]], Sprayberry High graduate, ''[[Extreme Home Makeover]]'' and ''[[Trading Spaces]]''\n*[[Cody Rhodes]], professional wrestler\n*[[Chris Robinson (singer)|Chris Robinson]] and [[Rich Robinson]] of [[The Black Crowes]]\n*[[Tony Schiavone]], former announcer for WCW, currently radio sports announcer, producer, engineer\n*[[Travis Tritt]], country music star\n*[[Lawson Vaughn]], professional soccer player\n*[[T. J. Yates]], NFL quarterback\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=yLN0dsWN57EC&pg=PA110&dq=east+cobb+georgia&hl=en&ei=_I-lTPufK4nCsAPz5fj9Dg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=east%20cobb%20georgia&f=false Rebecca Nash Paden, Joe McTyre, ''Cobb County'']\n\n{{Cobb County, Georgia}}\n{{Atlanta Metro}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Cobb County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Chattahoochee River]]\n", "name_user": "Trustmeonthisbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added for clarity.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Cobb,_Georgia"}
{"title_page": "Armistice of March 30, 1798", "text_new": "The '''armistice of March 30, 1798''' allowed [[Toussaint Louverture]] to settle the details of the retreat of the British army from [[Saint Domingue]], before the triumphal entry of the black general and his army of ex-slaves into [[Port-au-Prince]] on May 16, 1792. The aim of the armistice was the negotiations by which it was decided that the English would leave their last stronghold in the north of the country, [[M\u00f4le-Saint-Nicolas]], on August 31, 1798.\n\nFive months later, to the day, as planned, on August 31, 1798, the British abandoned Saint-Domingue to the victory of Toussaint Louverture, who must however turn to another front, to the south, where the former French general [[Andr\u00e9 Rigaud]] gathered an army of mulattoes with the help of French planters to fight it.\n\nThe armistice put an end to a war of liberation which left more than 10,000 dead and lasted four years: since the February 19, 1793, and the [[Treaty of Whitehall]], the English took advantage of the lucrative taxation on the sugar plantations of Santo Domingo, while since the May 5, 1794 Toussaint Louverture had launched an offensive.\n\nThe armistice was signed with the English general [[Thomas Maitland (British Army officer)|Thomas Maitland]], only three days after arrival, on March 27, 1798, of [[Gabriel, comte d'H\u00e9douville|H\u00e9douville]], sent from the directory, which must leave on October 23 of the same year, which mission was to discreetly incite Toussaint Louverture to engage his army in the attack on Jamaica and the United States, which the latter will be careful not to perform, to avoid losing all credit and part of his army. On the contrary, the black general would approach Maitland to encourage him too to trade.\n\nThe armistice of March 30, 1798 was signed shortly after the arrival in early March 1798 of young general Thomas Maitland at the head of the British army, who was instructed to limit English losses, especially as the month of March 1798 saw a wave of desertions among black enlisted by the British troops, who lose more strong.\n\nBy mid 1798, the U.S. Secretary of State [[Timothy Pickering]] confirmed that the United States would accept the resumption of commercial relations in case of victory of Toussaint Louverture, became then very likely scenario, and in November 1798 Toussaint Louverture sent [[Joseph Bunuel]] meet the main merchants of Philadelphia to negotiate the resumption of business, while the American State has given itself the means to rebuild a navy of war, in order to remove the French installed in Cuba, among which [[Pierre Lafitte|Pierre]] and [[Jean Lafitte]], who would feed the piracy of the 1800s in the Caribbean.\n\nOn June 13, 1799, Dr. [[Andrew Stevens]], officially appointed consul general of the United States in April 1799, signed the tripartite commercial convention of 1799, establishing commercial relations between English, Americans and Haitians.\n\nThe arrival in Cuba of refugees from Saint Domingue after the armistice of March 30, 1798 saw many become privateers during the quasi-war, which gives a first boost to commercial traffic in Cuba as shown by the values produced by the port of [[Santiago de Cuba]] between 1797 and 1801, a part coming from the catches of the French corsairs attacking the American ships trading with Saint Domingue.\n\nHowever, the armistice did not end the conflict within Saint Domingue, as [[Andr\u00e9 Rigaud]] would split with Louverture and initiate the [[War of Knives]] against him for control of the colony in June 1799 to July 1800, after which Rigaud fled to France and Louverture took command of the colony. Louverture would further consolidate control of the entire island by conquering the Spanish-ruled [[Captaincy General of Santo Domingo]] in December 1800 and abolishing chattel slavery throughout the island. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Haitian Revolution]]\n\n{{Haitian Revolution}}\n", "text_old": "The '''armistice of March 30, 1798''' allowed [[Toussaint Louverture]] to settle the details of the retreat of the British army from [[Saint Domingue]], before the triumphal entry of the black general and his army of ex-slaves into [[Port-au-Prince]] on May 16, 1792. The aim of the armistice was the negotiations by which it was decided that the English would leave their last stronghold in the north of the country, [[M\u00f4le-Saint-Nicolas]], on August 31, 1798.\n\nFive months later, to the day, as planned, on August 31, 1798, the British abandoned Saint-Domingue to the victory of Toussaint Louverture, who must however turn to another front, to the south, where the former French general [[Andr\u00e9 Rigaud]] gathered an army of mulattoes with the help of French planters to fight it.\n\nThe armistice put an end to a war of liberation which left more than 10,000 dead and lasted four years: since the February 19, 1793, and the [[Treaty of Whitehall]], the English took advantage of the lucrative taxation on the sugar plantations of Santo Domingo, while since the May 5, 1794 Toussaint Louverture had launched an offensive.\n\nThe armistice was signed with the English general [[Thomas Maitland (British Army officer)|Thomas Maitland]], only three days after arrival, on March 27, 1798, of [[Gabriel, comte d'H\u00e9douville|H\u00e9douville]], sent from the directory, which must leave on October 23 of the same year, which mission was to discreetly incite Toussaint Louverture to engage his army in the attack on Jamaica and the United States, which the latter will be careful not to perform, to avoid losing all credit and part of his army. On the contrary, the black general would approach Maitland to encourage him too to trade.\n\nThe armistice of March 30, 1798 was signed shortly after the arrival in early March 1798 of young general Thomas Maitland at the head of the British army, who was instructed to limit English losses, especially as the month of March 1798 saw a wave of desertions among black enlisted by the British troops, who lose more strong.\n\nBy mid 1798, the U.S. Secretary of State [[Timothy Pickering]] confirmed that the United States would accept the resumption of commercial relations in case of victory of Toussaint Louverture, became then very likely scenario, and in November 1798 Toussaint Louverture sent [[Joseph Bunuel]] meet the main merchants of Philadelphia to negotiate the resumption of business, while the American State has given itself the means to rebuild a navy of war, in order to remove the French installed in Cuba, among which [[Pierre Lafitte|Pierre]] and [[Jean Lafitte]], who would feed the piracy of the 1800s in the Caribbean.\n\nOn June 13, 1799, Dr. [[Andrew Stevens]], officially appointed consul general of the United States in April 1799, signed the tripartite commercial convention of 1799, establishing commercial relations between English, Americans and Haitians.\n\nThe arrival in Cuba of refugees from Saint Domingue after the armistice of March 30, 1798 saw many become privateers during the quasi-war, which gives a first boost to commercial traffic in Cuba as shown by the values produced by the port of [[Santiago de Cuba]] between 1797 and 1801, a part coming from the catches of the French corsairs attacking the American ships trading with Saint Domingue.\n\nHowever, the armistice did not end the conflict within Saint Domingue, as [[Andr\u00e9 Rigaud]] would split with Louverture and initiate the [[War of Knives]] against him for control of the colony in June 1799 to July 1800, after which Rigaud fled to France and Louverture took command of the colony. Louverture would further consolidate control of the entire island by conquering the Spanish-ruled [[Captaincy General of Santo Domingo]] in December 1800 and abolishing chattel slavery throughout the island. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Haitian Revolution]]\n\n{{Haitian Revolution\n", "name_user": "Infromerr", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armistice_of_March_30,_1798"}
{"title_page": "Sixteen Mile Creek (Halton Region)", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n| name               = Sixteen Mile Creek\n| name_native        = ''niizhozaagiwan'' {{allow wrap|(\"having two outlets\" in [[Eastern Ojibwa language|Mississauga]])}}\n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = ''Rivi\u00e8re de Gravois'' (\"gravelly river\" in [[French language|French]])\n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Sixteen Mile Creek Milton.jpg\n| image_caption      = Sixteen Mile at Milton, Ontario\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = Canada Southern Ontario\n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= Location of the mouth of Sixteen Mile Creek in southern Ontario\n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Canada]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Province\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Ontario]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Greater Toronto Area]]\n| subdivision_type4  = Regional Municipality\n| subdivision_name4  = [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton]]\n| subdivision_type5  = Municipalities\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Oakville, Ontario|Oakville]], [[Milton, Ontario|Milton]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             =  \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = [[wetland]]\n| source1_location   = [[Milton, Ontario|Milton]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|43|35|08|N|80|02|34|W|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|365|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[Lake Ontario]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Oakville, Ontario|Oakville]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|43|26|22|N|79|39|57|W|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|74|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = [[Great Lakes Basin]]\n| basin_size         = {{convert|372|km2|abbr=on}}\n| tributaries_left   = \n| tributaries_right  = \n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n\n'''Sixteen Mile Creek''' is a [[river]] in [[Halton Regional Municipality|Halton Region]] in the [[Greater Toronto Area]] of [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref name=\"CGNDB\">{{cite cgndb|id= FCOTA|title= Sixteen Mile Creek|accessdate= 2014-04-18}}</ref> It is in the [[Great Lakes Basin]], and flows from the [[Niagara Escarpment]] through the towns of [[Milton, Ontario|Milton]] and [[Oakville, Ontario|Oakville]] to [[Lake Ontario]].{{sfn|Dunn|p=4-6}}\n\nThe creek is named for the distance from the river's mouth to the western end of Lake Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oakvillegreen.org/discover-your-creek/sixteen-mile-creek-heart-of-the-halton-region/|title=Sixteen Mile Creek: Heart of the Halton Region|work=Oakville Conservation Association|accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref>  It was previously known to the [[Mississauga Indians]] in [[Eastern Ojibwa language|their language]] as ''Ne-sauga y-onk'' or ''niizhozaagiwan'' (\"having two outlets\")<ref>[http://www.freelang.net/online/ojibwe.php?lg=gb FREELANG Ojibwe-English and English-Ojibwe online dictionary]</ref> and to the French as ''Rivi\u00e8re de Gravois'' (\"gravelly river\").<ref>{{Cite web|title = French Sketch Map, c. 1760|url = http://images.burlington.halinet.on.ca/9469/data|accessdate = 2012-02-22}}</ref>\n\nLike many creeks draining into Lake Ontario, Sixteen Mile Creek has cut a deep valley that is home to a broad range of wildlife, including whitetail deer, raccoons, foxes, opossum, and squirrels.{{sfn|Dunn|p=110-112}} The forest contains tree species typical of the [[Carolinian forest]] habitat,{{sfn|Dunn|p=52}} although since this is close to the northern limit of this zone, some are poorly represented. The total area of the [[drainage basin]] is {{convert|372|km2|sqmi}}.{{sfn|Dunn|p=4}}\n\nIn Oakville, it also forms part of [[Glen Abbey Golf Course]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Witteveen|first=Gordon|title=A century of greenkeeping|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iZjB0fXZEPkC&pg=PA149|accessdate=16 February 2012|year=2001|location= Chelsea, Mich|publisher= Ann Arbor Press|isbn=978-1-57504-161-2|oclc= 46364702|page= 149}}</ref> and is home to the [[Oakville Yacht Squadron]].<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Inland seas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VRIUAAAAYAAJ|title= Unknown title|accessdate=16 February 2012|volume= 18|year=1962|publisher=Great Lakes Historical Society|issn= 0020-1537|page= 59}}</ref>\n\n==Tributaries==\n*East Sixteen Mile Creek (left)\n*Middle Sixteen Mile Creek (left)\nMy name is Bob.\n\n==Invasive species==\n[[Giant hogweed]] is a non-native invasive plant that is most widely distributed in Halton Region along Sixteen Mile Creek. Contact with this plant can cause serious burns to the skin and temporary or permanent blindness.<ref>http://www.halton.ca/cms/one.aspx?pageId=47106</ref><ref>http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/5766594-giant-hogweed-continues-to-sprout-in-milton/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kelso Conservation Area]]\n* [[List of rivers of Ontario]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite web|ref=harv|url=http://www.craa.on.ca/pdf/16MileProjectReport.pdf|title=Sixteen Mile Creek Monitoring Project (Draft)|last=Dunn|first=Andrea|publisher=Credit River Anglers Association|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zxLZfx5M|archivedate=5 July 2011}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite map|url= http://www.mto.gov.on.ca/english/traveller/map/images/pdf/southont/sheets/Map3.pdf |format= PDF|title= Map 3|series= Official road map of Ontario|publisher= [[Ministry of Transportation of Ontario]]|scale= 1 : 700,000|date= 2010-01-01|accessdate= 2014-04-18}}\n*{{cite map|url= http://www.mah.gov.on.ca/AssetFactory.aspx?did=6577 |title= Restructured municipalities - Ontario map #6|year= 2006|series= Restructuring Maps of Ontario|publisher= [[Ministry of Municipal Affairs and Housing (Ontario)|Ontario Ministry of Municipal Affairs and Housing]]|accessdate= 2014-04-18}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.oakvilletrails.ca/is-sixteen.htm Information on the creek and valley]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{greatlakes}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Landforms of the Regional Municipality of Halton]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of Lake Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n| name               = Sixteen Mile Creek\n| name_native        = ''niizhozaagiwan'' {{allow wrap|(\"having two outlets\" in [[Eastern Ojibwa language|Mississauga]])}}\n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = ''Rivi\u00e8re de Gravois'' (\"gravelly river\" in [[French language|French]])\n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Sixteen Mile Creek Milton.jpg\n| image_caption      = Sixteen Mile at Milton, Ontario\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = Canada Southern Ontario\n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= Location of the mouth of Sixteen Mile Creek in southern Ontario\n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Canada]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Province\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Ontario]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Greater Toronto Area]]\n| subdivision_type4  = Regional Municipality\n| subdivision_name4  = [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton]]\n| subdivision_type5  = Municipalities\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Oakville, Ontario|Oakville]], [[Milton, Ontario|Milton]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             =  \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = [[wetland]]\n| source1_location   = [[Milton, Ontario|Milton]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|43|35|08|N|80|02|34|W|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|365|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[Lake Ontario]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Oakville, Ontario|Oakville]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|43|26|22|N|79|39|57|W|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|74|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = [[Great Lakes Basin]]\n| basin_size         = {{convert|372|km2|abbr=on}}\n| tributaries_left   = \n| tributaries_right  = \n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n\n'''Sixteen Mile Creek''' is a [[river]] in [[Halton Regional Municipality|Halton Region]] in the [[Greater Toronto Area]] of [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref name=\"CGNDB\">{{cite cgndb|id= FCOTA|title= Sixteen Mile Creek|accessdate= 2014-04-18}}</ref> It is in the [[Great Lakes Basin]], and flows from the [[Niagara Escarpment]] through the towns of [[Milton, Ontario|Milton]] and [[Oakville, Ontario|Oakville]] to [[Lake Ontario]].{{sfn|Dunn|p=4-6}}\n\nThe creek is named for the distance from the river's mouth to the western end of Lake Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oakvillegreen.org/discover-your-creek/sixteen-mile-creek-heart-of-the-halton-region/|title=Sixteen Mile Creek: Heart of the Halton Region|work=Oakville Conservation Association|accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref>  It was previously known to the [[Mississauga Indians]] in [[Eastern Ojibwa language|their language]] as ''Ne-sauga y-onk'' or ''niizhozaagiwan'' (\"having two outlets\")<ref>[http://www.freelang.net/online/ojibwe.php?lg=gb FREELANG Ojibwe-English and English-Ojibwe online dictionary]</ref> and to the French as ''Rivi\u00e8re de Gravois'' (\"gravelly river\").<ref>{{Cite web|title = French Sketch Map, c. 1760|url = http://images.burlington.halinet.on.ca/9469/data|accessdate = 2012-02-22}}</ref>\n\nLike many creeks draining into Lake Ontario, Sixteen Mile Creek has cut a deep valley that is home to a broad range of wildlife, including whitetail deer, raccoons, foxes, opossum, and squirrels.{{sfn|Dunn|p=110-112}} The forest contains tree species typical of the [[Carolinian forest]] habitat,{{sfn|Dunn|p=52}} although since this is close to the northern limit of this zone, some are poorly represented. The total area of the [[drainage basin]] is {{convert|372|km2|sqmi}}.{{sfn|Dunn|p=4}}\n\nIn Oakville, it also forms part of [[Glen Abbey Golf Course]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Witteveen|first=Gordon|title=A century of greenkeeping|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iZjB0fXZEPkC&pg=PA149|accessdate=16 February 2012|year=2001|location= Chelsea, Mich|publisher= Ann Arbor Press|isbn=978-1-57504-161-2|oclc= 46364702|page= 149}}</ref> and is home to the [[Oakville Yacht Squadron]].<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Inland seas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VRIUAAAAYAAJ|title= Unknown title|accessdate=16 February 2012|volume= 18|year=1962|publisher=Great Lakes Historical Society|issn= 0020-1537|page= 59}}</ref>\n\n==Tributaries==\n*East Sixteen Mile Creek (left)\n*Middle Sixteen Mile Creek (left)\n\n==Invasive species==\n[[Giant hogweed]] is a non-native invasive plant that is most widely distributed in Halton Region along Sixteen Mile Creek. Contact with this plant can cause serious burns to the skin and temporary or permanent blindness.<ref>http://www.halton.ca/cms/one.aspx?pageId=47106</ref><ref>http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/5766594-giant-hogweed-continues-to-sprout-in-milton/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kelso Conservation Area]]\n* [[List of rivers of Ontario]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite web|ref=harv|url=http://www.craa.on.ca/pdf/16MileProjectReport.pdf|title=Sixteen Mile Creek 